THIRD-PARTY COMPONENTS
================================================================================

DRAMATIS downloads and depends on the following at runtime. None of it is
vendored into this repository.

Kokoro-82M
  https://huggingface.co/hexgrad/Kokoro-82M
  Apache License 2.0. Used for narration.

Qwen3-TTS and Qwen3-ForcedAligner
  https://github.com/QwenLM
  Apache License 2.0, Alibaba Cloud. Used for local character voices, voice
  cloning, and word-level forced alignment.

LAION-CLAP
  https://github.com/LAION-AI/CLAP
  Apache License 2.0. Used for text-to-audio retrieval of sound effects.

ACE-Step 1.5 (optional)
  https://github.com/ACE-Step/ACE-Step-1.5
  MIT License (code and model weights). Optional free/local music engine; the
  user installs it separately and DRAMATIS talks to its local API.

kokoro-onnx
  Installed from PyPI. NOTE: this package depends on phonemizer-fork, which is
  licensed GPL-3.0 and calls espeak-ng. Nothing GPL is vendored or distributed
  here — it is installed into the user's own Python environment at setup time.
  Anyone REDISTRIBUTING DRAMATIS as a bundled binary (Docker image, Tauri or
  Electron app, installer) must satisfy GPL-3.0 for that bundle, or swap the
  phonemizer backend first.

FSD50K
  https://zenodo.org/records/4060432
  Eduardo Fonseca, Xavier Favory, Jordi Pons, Frederic Font, Xavier Serra.
  "FSD50K: an Open Dataset of Human-Labeled Sound Events."
  IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, 2022.

  The DRAMATIS sound-effect corpus is built from the CC0-licensed subset of
  FSD50K. Note that the FSD50K dataset AS A WHOLE is released under CC-BY 4.0,
  which requires attribution regardless of the licences of individual clips —
  hence this citation. FSD50K aggregates community recordings from Freesound
  (https://freesound.org). If you extend the corpus beyond the CC0 subset, you
  must honour each clip's own licence and its contributor's attribution terms.

Public-domain manuscripts in samples/
  "The Monkey's Paw", W. W. Jacobs, 1902.
  "The Open Window", Saki (H. H. Munro), from the collection
    "Beasts and Super-Beasts", 1914 (Project Gutenberg #269).
  "The Signal-Man", Charles Dickens, 1866.
  All are in the public domain in the United States and in life+70
